Cape Town â€“ A tip-off led to an Ethiopian national being arrested in Mossel Bay on Wednesday for illegally selling cigarettes. According to Eastern Cape police spokesperson Captain Malcolm Pojie, police arrested the 32-year-old suspect at his shop in KwaNonqaba township for contravention of the lockdown regulations as well as the sale of cigarettes. More than 1 000 cartons of cigarettes, worth about R10 000, were confiscated, Pojie said. The suspect paid a R1 000 fine before being released. Meanwhile, a 39-year-old man was caught allegedly transporting illicit cigarettes in Boithuso, Free State. It is alleged he later tried to bribe police officers. Police spokesperson Brigadier Motantsi Makhele said the man was caught on Friday morning with cigarettes worth R636 800 after officers on patrol had stopped a panel van driving on a gravel road. "The police followed the suspect's vehicle, stopped it and requested a permit from the driver who failed to produce one. "The driver was then requested to drive to the police station for further interrogation. On the way, he stopped his vehicle and allegedly offered police a R5 000 bribe," said Makhele. Police found eight boxes filled with cigarettes in the van. The suspect later allegedly increased his offer to R15 000. He van was confiscated by the police and he faces charges of bribery and dealing in illicit cigarettes. Cape Times